The '''2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final''' was a [[association football|soccer]] match between the [[Seattle Sounders FC]] and the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]], played on October 4, 2011, at [[CenturyLink Field]] in [[Seattle]], Washington. The match was the culmination of the [[2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup]], a tournament open to amateur and professional soccer teams affiliated with the [[United States Soccer Federation]] (U.S. Soccer). This was the 98th edition of the [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]], the oldest ongoing competition in American soccer. The Seattle Sounders FC won by defeating the Chicago Fire 2<U+2013>0 with goals scored by [[Fredy Montero]] and [[Osvaldo Alonso]]. The attendance was 36,615, breaking the record for the final set the previous year when Seattle also won and hosted. Seattle became the first team since 1968 to win three consecutive U.S. Open Cup championships and the fourth team ever to do so in the 98-year history of the tournament.

Sounders FC automatically qualified for the third round of the U.S. Open Cup tournament by finishing among the top six in the [[2010 Major League Soccer season]]. The Fire did not automatically qualify, and had to play through two [[2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup qualification|qualification rounds]] before entering the official tournament. Prior to the final, Chicago and Seattle had met twice in 2011, with Seattle winning one game and the other ending in a draw.

The final was televised live on [[Fox Soccer]]. This was the second consecutive year the tournament final was played at CenturyLink Field.  As the winner of the tournament, Seattle earned a berth in the [[2012<U+2013>13 CONCACAF Champions League]] and received a $100,000 cash prize. Chicago received a $50,000 prize as the runner-up. Following the final, criticism was raised regarding Seattle winning hosting rights for each round they played. In response, U.S. Soccer announced changes to the rules for determining the host of tournament matches.

== Road to the final ==
{{details|2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup}}
The U.S. Open Cup is an annual American soccer competition open to all U.S. Soccer affiliated teams, from amateur adult club teams to the professional clubs of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS). The 2011 tournament was the 98th edition of the oldest soccer tournament in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/sports/stories/2010/10/06/crew-falls-in-open-cup-final.html |title=Soccer: Crew falls in Open Cup final |first=Shawn |last=Mitchell |date=October 5, 2010 |newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch |accessdate=September 3, 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101013092633/http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/sports/stories/2010/10/06/crew-falls-in-open-cup-final.html| archivedate= October 13, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The MLS, which has teams that play in both the United States and Canada, was allowed to enter eight of its fifteen U.S.-based teams in the tournament. The top six MLS teams from the [[2010 Major League Soccer season|previous season's]] league standings qualified automatically for the tournament, while the remaining two spots were determined by [[2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup qualification|preliminary qualification matches]].<ref name="USOC101">{{cite web |url=http://www.portlandtimbers.com/news/2011/03/mls-101-primer-2011-tournament-structure |title=MLS 101: A primer on the 2011 tournament structure |first=Mark |last=Nelson |date=March 28, 2011 |publisher=Portland Timbers |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> The eight MLS entries began play in the third round of the tournament. In 2010, Seattle Sounders FC finished among the top six in the MLS overall league standings to qualify for the third round of the 2011 U.S. Open Cup.<ref name="USOC101"/> The Chicago Fire however, did not and therefore had to play a series of qualification matches against fellow MLS teams that finished outside of the top six to qualify for the Open Cup tournament.<ref name="USOC101"/>

=== Chicago Fire ===
{{see also|2011 Chicago Fire season}}
{{quote box |align=right |width=22% |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |quote=We've talked about the success and meaning of the tournament recently. That success started long before I was here. Winning the double in 1998, then winning again in 2000. My first year was 2003 when we won it and I was here in 2006. It's been a tournament this club has put a lot of effort, energy and money into being successful in. |source=[[Logan Pause]], Chicago Fire captain<ref name="FireImportance">{{cite web |url=http://www.chicago-fire.com/news/2011/07/open-cup-importance |title=Open Cup Importance |first=Jeff |last=Crandall |date=July 12, 2011 |publisher=Chicago Fire |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>}}Prior to reaching the 2011 final, the Chicago Fire had reached the U.S. Open Cup final five times in their 14-year history, the most of any MLS franchise, winning four out of five of the tournaments&ndash;most recently in 2006.<ref name="FireImportance"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicago-fire.com/news/2011/07/open-cup-lore |title=Open Cup Lore |first=Tom |last=Dunmore |date=July 11, 2011 |publisher=Chicago Fire |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> The Fire began their 2011 Open Cup campaign on March 30, 2011, in the MLS qualification semifinals, hosting the [[Colorado Rapids]] at [[Shea Stadium (Peoria, Illinois)|Shea Stadium]] in [[Peoria, Illinois]]. Chicago scored first with a goal from [[Gast<U+00F3>n Puerari]] right before half time. Just one minute into the second half, the Rapids equalized off of a goal from [[Andre Akpan]]. Following Akpan's goal, the match remained tied for 15 minutes until Chicago's [[Jalil Anibaba]] scored the match-winning goal in the 61st minute of play.  Chicago moved on to the next round of qualification with a final score of 2<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coloradorapids.com/news/2011/03/open-cup-colorado-1-chicago-2 |title=Open Cup: Colorado 1, Chicago 2 |first=German |last=Sferra |date=March 31, 2011 |publisher=Colorado Rapids |accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref>

The Fire then turned their attention to their second and final qualification match hosted by the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] at [[Buck Shaw Stadium]] in [[Santa Clara, California]]. Played on May 24, 2011, in front of 4,124 spectators, the hosts took a two-goal lead in the first half with [[Ellis McLoughlin]] and [[Justin Morrow]] scoring in the 14th and 43rd minutes, respectively. The Fire halved the deficit in the 61st minute with a goal from [[Orr Barouch]]. Fifteen minutes later the Fire tied the score with a strike from [[Yamith Cuesta]]. The score remained tied until the end of regulation, leading to [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]], during which Chicago's [[Gonzalo Segares]] was [[Foul (association football)#Red card .28dismissal.29|ejected]] for dissent. Despite the Earthquakes' man advantage, the two sides remained tied during overtime, prompting a [[penalty shootout]]. In the fifth round of penalties, with Chicago leading 5<U+2013>4, San Jose's [[Scott Sealy]] missed his shot as it deflected off of the crossbar, giving the Fire a second qualifier victory and a berth into the third round of the 2011 U.S. Open Cup tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lepper |first=Geoff |title=USOC: Fire edge Quakes in PKs, through to round of 16 |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/05/25/usoc-fire-edge-quakes-pks-thru-round-16 |work=Major League Soccer |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=May 25, 2010 |accessdate=August 31, 2011}}</ref>

In the third round, Chicago faced the [[Rochester Rhinos]] of the [[USL Pro]] division.<ref>{{cite web |last=Barnhart |first=Gerald |title=2011 Third round MLS pairing scenarios announced; Rochester only lower division team to host |url=http://thecup.us/2011-third-round-mls-pairing-scenarios-announce-rochester-only-lower-division-team-to-host/ |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=August 31, 2011 |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Rochester hosted the match on June 28 at the Rhinos' [[Sahlen's Stadium]] in front of a crowd of 5,558. The Fire's [[Diego Ch<U+00E1>ves]] netted the match's only goal in the 37th minute of play, earning the Fire a spot in the quarterfinals for the first time since 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicago-fire.com/news/2011/06/fire-1-0-rhinos |title=Fire 1 <U+2013> 0 Rhinos |date=June 29, 2011 |publisher=Chicago Fire |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>

In the quarterfinals, held on July 12, 2011, the Fire hosted MLS [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] rival the [[New York Red Bulls]] at [[Toyota Park (Bridgeview)|Toyota Park]] in [[Bridgeview, Illinois]].  Against mostly [[MLS Reserve League|reserves]] for New York, the Fire won the match 4<U+2013>0 with two goals from Orr Barouch and a goal each scored by [[Dominic Oduro]] and [[Yamith Cuesta]].  Due to power outages in the area following a severe thunderstorm, the game's start time was moved up from 7:30&nbsp;pm to 5:00&nbsp;pm local time, resulting in a late-arriving attendance of about 2,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-07-12/sports/ct-spt-0713-fire-chicago--20110713_1_bouna-coundoul-fire-advances-fire-outshot |title=Fire rout Red Bulls 4<U+2013>0 |first=Jack |last=McCarthy |date=July 12, 2011 |newspaper=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicago-fire.com/news/2011/07/next-one |title=On to the Next One |date=July 13, 2011 |publisher=Chicago Fire |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>  Following the match, uproar from Red Bull fans prompted coach [[Hans Backe]] to explain that fatigue was the reason for sending only his team's reserve players and an assistant coach to Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/news/2011/07/rbny-notebook-traveling-too-much-usoc-says-backe |title=RBNY Notebook: Traveling too much for USOC, says Backe |first=Kristian |last=Dyer |date=July 14, 2011 |publisher=New York Red Bulls |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> New York had lost to DC United in league play just 2 days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcunited.com/news/2011/07/recap-new-york-red-bulls-0-dc-united-1 |title=Recap: New York Red Bulls 0 - D.C. United 1 |first=Kristian |last=Dyer |date=July 9, 2011 |publisher=DC United |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref>

On August 31, 2011, the Fire played host to another USL Pro side, the [[Richmond Kickers]], in the semifinal round. On their way to the semifinals, the Kickers defeated two MLS teams in consecutive rounds. They upset the [[Columbus Crew]] and [[Sporting Kansas City]] in the third round and the quarterfinals, respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.timesdispatch.com/sports/2011/aug/30/tdsport03-kickers-chicago-fire-preview-capsule-ar-1272678/ |title=Kickers-Chicago Fire preview capsule |date=August 30, 2011 |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.timesdispatch.com/sports/pro-sports/2011/jul/14/tdsport01-kickers-show-grit-in-victory-ar-1171535/ |title=Kickers show grit in victory |first=Vic |last=Dorr Jr. |date=July 14, 2011 |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref> The semifinal was hosted by the Fire at Toyota Park in front of a crowd of 8,909.  In the 32nd minute, the Fire took the lead with a goal from [[Sebasti<U+00E1>n Grazzini]]. In the 61st minute, Chicago went up 2&ndash;0 with a goal from Dominic Oduro. Seven minutes later, the Kickers cut the lead in half with a goal from [[Yomby William]]. The Fire won 2<U+2013>1, earning their sixth trip to the U.S. Open Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorfman |first=Daniel |title=Kickers fall to Chicago Fire, 2<U+2013>1 |url=http://www2.timesdispatch.com/sports/2011/aug/31/tdsport01-kickers-fall-to-chicago-fire-2-1-ar-1275255/ |newspaper=Richmond Times-Dispatch |accessdate=August 31, 2011 |date=August 31, 2011}}</ref>

=== Seattle Sounders FC ===
{{see also|2011 Seattle Sounders FC season}}
{{quote box |align=left |width=22% |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |quote=We want to accomplish something that no MLS team has done by winning three in a row.  Any time we can make an achievement that sets us apart, it's important to our club. |source=[[Sigi Schmid]], Seattle Sounders FC head coach<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016051221_sounders30.html |title=Sounders FC hosts FC Dallas in U.S. Open Cup semifinal |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=August 29, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>}}
In 2009, Seattle Sounders FC became the second MLS [[Expansion team|expansion club]] to win the [[2009 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final|U.S. Open Cup tournament]], after the Chicago Fire in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seattle Sounders FC Become Second MLS Expansion Team to Claim U.S. Open Cup Crown |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2009/09/Seattle-Sounders-Become-Second-Expansion-Team-to-Claim-US-Open-Cup-Crown.aspx |publisher=U.S. Soccer |date=September 2, 2009 |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref> They defended their title in 2010 to win a second straight championship.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2015444198_sounders28.html |title=Sounders FC ready to defend U.S. Open Cup title |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=June 27, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2010/10/Seattle-Sounders-FC-Repeats-as-Lamar-Hunt-US-Open-Cup-Champions-with-21-Win-against-Columbus-Crew.aspx |title=Seattle Sounders FC Earn Second Consecutive Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Title in Front of Record-Setting Crowd at Qwest Field |date=October 5, 2010 |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>  Prior to the final, Sounders FC played U.S. Open Cup home games at the [[Starfire Sports Complex]] in [[Tukwila, Washington]]. The facility is smaller than the club's home stadium for league matches, [[CenturyLink Field]], but Sounders FC representatives preferred the atmosphere at Starfire for smaller cup matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/seattlesports/archives/169659.asp |title=Colorado coach miffed at Sounders' playing facility |accessdate=March 15, 2011 |first=Greg |last=Johns |date=May 7, 2009 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j0w4PRBg |archivedate=August 14, 2009 |deadurl=no}}</ref>

Sounders FC began the defense of their title on June 28, 2011, when they hosted the [[Kitsap Pumas]] of the [[USL Premier Development League]] from [[Bremerton, Washington]].  The match was played at Starfire in front of 3,811 fans.<ref name="PumasResult">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2015454097_sounders29.html |title=Sounders FC fends off pesky Kitsap Pumas in U.S. Open Cup action, 2<U+2013>1 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=June 28, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>  Seattle took the lead in the 39th minute when [[Michael Fucito]] scored off a headed pass from [[Nate Jaqua]].  Early in the second half Fucito doubled the lead by taking a pass from [[Mike Seamon]] and shooting past several defenders for the goal.  Kitsap attempted their comeback in the 71st minute when [[Nikolas Besagno]] scored off of a crossing pass from Robert Christner.  In the 83rd minute, Kitsap forward Warlen Silva nearly equalized on a breakaway run, but his shot went into the side netting.  Seattle was able to hold on for the 2<U+2013>1 victory.<ref name="PumasResult"/>

[[File:July 13 2011 Sounders v LA Galaxy.jpg|thumb|right|[[Seattle Sounders FC|Seattle's]] second half kickoff vs. the [[Los Angeles Galaxy|LA Galaxy]] at [[Starfire Sports Complex|Starfire]].|alt=Two players stand over a soccer ball at the center of the field while a referee holds his hand over head.]]
Seattle then hosted their quarterfinal match on July 13 against a fellow MLS side, the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].  The match was again held at Starfire, with an attendance of 4,322.  Nate Jaqua scored following a pass from [[Pat Noonan]] in the 4th minute.  In the 25th minute, [[Fredy Montero]] scored with a left footed shot off of an assist from Jaqua giving Seattle a 2<U+2013>0 lead.  The Galaxy gained a goal back in the 40th minute when [[Adam Cristman]] scored on a cross from [[Chris Birchall]].  In the 74th minute, Seattle midfielder [[Lamar Neagle]] scored from a cross by [[<U+00C1>lvaro Fern<U+00E1>ndez]], extending Seattle's lead to 2 goals.<ref name="LAResult">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2015603385_sounders14.html |title=Sounders FC beats Galaxy 3<U+2013>1 in U.S. Open Cup quarterfinal |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=July 13, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>

On August 30, 2011, Sounders FC hosted their semifinal opponent, [[FC Dallas]], in front of 4,593 at Starfire Sports Complex.  Both teams started their first team players for the match.<ref name="DallasResult">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016060456_sounders31.html |title=Sounders FC wins 1<U+2013>0, will host Open Cup final vs. Chicago on October 4 |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=August 30, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 3, 2011}}</ref>  Seattle applied offensive pressure for most of the first half and broke through with a goal in the 40th minute.  Fredy Montero, who had just missed with a [[bicycle kick]] shot moments earlier, took a curling left-footed shot in front of goal for the score.  Dallas nearly equalized in the 49th minute when [[Marvin Chavez]] had a shot bounce hard off of the [[goal post]].  Dallas continued to attack for most of the second half, and Chavez again had a chance to equalize just before the final whistle, but his shot went high over the goal.  With a final score of 1<U+2013>0, Seattle secured their third straight appearance in the U.S. Open Cup final match.<ref name="DallasResult"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tri-cityherald.com/2011/08/31/1621839/monteros-goal-puts-sounders-in.html |title=Montero's goal puts Sounders in final |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=August 31, 2011 |newspaper=Tri-City Herald |accessdate=September 26, 2013}}</ref>  Following the match, Dallas coach [[Schellas Hyndman]] complained about how hosts are determined for U.S. Open Cup matches saying, "for me, this is one of the best events <U+2013> the Lamar Hunt Open Cup <U+2013> but I'd really like to see it into a structure where it's not a bid system. A bid system is where one team will buy the games because they're bidding higher."  He continued, "it could go to the higher seeds, instead of a bid system where you're spending money, or it could be pre-determined. I think that brings out all the fairness to the event."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016060619_sounders_fc_1_fc_dallas_0_post.html |title=Sounders FC 1, FC Dallas 0, postgame quotes and stats |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=August 30, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref>

{{clear}}

== Pre-match ==

=== Venue selection ===
[[File:Aerial CenturyLink Field November 2011.jpg|thumb|CenturyLink Field in Seattle|alt=Aerial view of a stadium.]]
On August 26, 2011, U.S. Soccer announced the potential sites for the final, depending on the outcome of the semifinals.  It was determined through a blind bid process that if Seattle qualified for the final, they would host it at CenturyLink Field regardless of the opponent, for the second straight year.  If FC Dallas defeated Sounders FC in the semifinals, they would host the Richmond Kickers at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], or visit the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] at Toyota Park in [[Bridgeview, Illinois]], depending on the outcome of the other semifinal match.<ref name="host selection">{{cite web |title=U.S. Soccer Announces Possible Hosts for 2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2011/08/US-Soccer-Announces-Possible-Hosts-for-the-2011-Lamar-Hunt-US-Open-Cup-Final.aspx |publisher=U.S. Soccer Federation |accessdate=August 31, 2011 |date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Seattle defeated Dallas and Chicago defeated Richmond in the semifinals, which resulted in Sounders FC hosting the Fire in the 2011 Open Cup final at CenturyLink Field.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/soccer/chi-fire-to-visit-sounders-for-us-open-cup-title-20110831,0,4242256.story |title=Fire to visit Sounders for U.S. Open Cup title |first=Jack |last=McCarthy |date=August 31, 2011 |newspaper=The Chicago Tribune |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref>  Seattle had hosted the previous final, in 2010, drawing a crowd of 31,311<ref>{{cite web |title=Seattle Sounders FC Earn Second Consecutive Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Title in Front of Record-Setting Crowd at Qwest Field |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2010/10/Seattle-Sounders-FC-Repeats-as-Lamar-Hunt-US-Open-Cup-Champions-with-21-Win-against-Columbus-Crew.aspx |publisher=U.S. Soccer |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=October 9, 2010 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101009132755/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2010/10/Seattle-Sounders-FC-Repeats-as-Lamar-Hunt-US-Open-Cup-Champions-with-21-Win-against-Columbus-Crew.aspx |archivedate=October 9, 2010 <!--DASHBot--> |deadurl=no}}</ref> and breaking the 81-year-old attendance record for the event set in [[1929 National Challenge Cup|1929]] when [[New York Hakoah]] defeated the [[St. Louis Madison Kennel|Madison Kennel Club of St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2012889535_youve_done_it_again_--_22000_t.html |title=You've done it again <U+2013> 22,000 tickets sold for Open Cup final |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=September 13, 2010 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 14, 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100915232424/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2012889535_youve_done_it_again_--_22000_t.html |archivedate= September 15, 2010 <!--DASHBot--> |deadurl= no}}</ref>

Tickets for the 2011 final went on sale to the public on September 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016067235_us_open_cup_final_tickets_go_o.html |title=U.S. Open Cup final tickets go on sale at 10&nbsp;am Tuesday |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=August 31, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref>  By September 19, it was announced that 27,000 tickets had already been sold.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016257084_more_than_27000_tickets_sold_f.html |title=More than 27,000 tickets sold for the U.S. Open Cup final |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=September 19, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/09/19/sounders-about-4000-shy-of-open-cup-record-crowd/ |title=Seattle about 4,000 from Open Cup record crowd |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=September 19, 2011 |newspaper=The News Tribune |accessdate=September 20, 2011}}</ref> Nine days later, ticket sales surpassed 30,000 and it was announced that the "Hawks Nest" [[bleacher]] seats in the north end of CenturyLink Field would be made available for the event.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016348966_more_than_30000_tickets_sold_f.html |title=More than 30,000 tickets sold for the U.S. Open Cup final, Sounders FC to open up the Hawks Nest to satisfy demand |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=September 28, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/09/28/30000-sold-sounders-open-more-seats-for-cup-final/ |title=30,000 sold, more seats opened for Cup final |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=September 28, 2011 |newspaper=The News Tribune |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> In the week leading up to the final, Sounders FC owner and general manager Adrian Hanauer indicated that sections of the stadium would continue to be opened to meet demand.  He stated that "no paying customer would be turned away."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016388728_gm_adrian_hanauer_expects_arou.html |title=GM Adrian Hanauer expects around 35,000 for USOC final |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 2, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>

=== Analysis ===
With a better MLS regular season record and home field advantage, Sounders FC were the favorites to win the match; however, the Fire had improved throughout the year through better play from their [[Forward (association football)#Winger|wingers]] and [[midfielders]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016392656_poll_how_nervous_are_you_of_th.html |title=Poll: How nervous are you of the Chicago Fire? |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=October 3, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |last=Mayers |first=Joshua}}</ref>

Seattle and Chicago had met twice in MLS regular season matches in 2011.  The first meeting, on April 9, 2011, resulted in a 2<U+2013>1 win for Sounders FC in front of their home crowd.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2014732761_apsocmlsfiresounders2ndldwritethru.html |title=White scores again, Sounders beat Fire 2<U+2013>1 |date=April 9, 2011 |newspaper=The Associated Press |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref>  It was Seattle's 5th game of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2014732535_sounders10.html |title=Sounders FC back in the win column |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=April 9, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref> The second meeting was hosted by Chicago on June 4, 2011, and resulted in a 0<U+2013>0 draw.  It was the first game for Chicago coach [[Frank Klopas]] as he replaced [[Carlos de los Cobos]], who was fired by the club the previous week.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2015236181_sounders05.html |title=Sounders pick up point with draw at Chicago |first=Bob |last=Hurst |date=June 4, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref> As a player, Klopas had scored the winning goal for Chicago in the [[1998 U.S. Open Cup|1998 U.S. Open Cup final]].  As coach, ''ESPNChicago.com'' analyst Charlie Corr credited him with the team's successful shift in tactics since previously meeting Seattle.<ref name="Corr 2011-10-3">{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago/fire/post/_/id/2073/fires-klopas-vying-for-open-cup-as-coach |title=Fire's Klopas vying for Open Cup as coach |publisher=ESPN |date=October 3, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2011 |author=Corr, Charlie}}</ref>

In the days leading up to the final, Seattle had recently finished a long road trip.  Chicago's schedule made the match their third in a week's time. In preparation for the final, the managers fielded weaker sides during their respective league matches two days before the game, allowing them to rest several regular starters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/10/03/sounders-notebook-seattle-rested-ahead-usoc-final |title=Sounders Notebook: Seattle rested ahead of USOC final |first=Andrew |last=Winner |date=October 3, 2011 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/10/03/usoc-preview-seattle-chicago-primed-open-cup-final |title=USOC Preview: Seattle, Chicago primed for Open Cup final |first=Nate |last=Sulat |date=October 3, 2011 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Corr 2011-10-01">{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/chicago/fire/post/_/id/2056/oduro-fire-rally-to-draw-dynamo |title=Oduro, Fire rally to draw Dynamo |publisher=ESPN |date=October 1, 2011 |accessdate=October 2, 2011 |author=Corr, Charlie}}</ref>  The Sounders were playing well, having already clinched a [[2011 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS playoff]] berth. A victory over the [[New England Revolution]] on the weekend prior to the final gave the team a three-game winning streak.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/10/01/sounders-top-revolution-to-tune-up-for-cup-final/ |title=Sounders top Revolution to tune up for Cup final |publisher=Fox News |date=October 1, 2011 |accessdate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> The Fire had defeated [[Real Salt Lake]] on September 28, but their playoff chances were diminished after a tie against the [[Houston Dynamo]] on the weekend prior to the final.<ref name="Corr 2011-10-01"/>

== Match ==
The match was televised live on [[Fox Soccer]] with coverage starting at 7&nbsp;pm [[Pacific Time Zone|PT]] (2&nbsp;am [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2011/08/Chicago-and-Seattle-Will-Face-Off-in-2011-Lamar-Hunt-US-Open-Cup-Final.aspx |title=Chicago Fire and Seattle Sounders Will Face Off in 2011 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final |date=August 31, 2011 |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> The attendance of 36,615 was a record crowd for the competition's final.<ref name="FOX Chicago 2011-10-5">{{cite news |url=http://www.myfoxchicago.com/story/17822794/sounders-beat-fire-in-us-cup-final |title=Sounders Beat Fire In US Cup Final |publisher=FOX Chicago News |date=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref> Seattle's [[Emerald City Supporters]] unveiled [[tifo]] before kickoff depicting the [[Grim Reaper]] over the graves of [[D.C. United]], the Columbus Crew, and the Chicago Fire.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016416313_video_of_the_impressive_ecs_ti.html |title=Video of the Impressive ECS Tifo and Other Open Cup Notes |work=The Seattle Times |date=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=October 6, 2011 |last=Mayers |first=Joshua}}</ref>

Injuries to key players were a concern for both teams in the build up to the final.  For Seattle, midfielder [[Mauro Rosales]]'s knee was injured and he did not recover in time for the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/02/rosales-will-be-gametime-decision-tuesday/ |title=Rosales will be gametime decision Tuesday |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 2, 2011 |newspaper=Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Also, Sounders FC defender [[James Riley (soccer)|James Riley]] was recovering from a concussion. He practiced in the week prior to the final and started in the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/03/rosales-riley-trained-today-but-tomorrow-still-uncertain/ |title=Rosales, Riley trained today; tomorrow uncertain |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 3, 2011 |newspaper=Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016389301_sunday_practice_notes_rosales.html |title=Sunday practice notes: Rosales and Riley improving |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 3, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>  For Chicago, midfielder Sebastian Grazzini was a key player who was questionable before the match.<ref name="Corr 2011-10-3"/><ref>{{cite video |date= October 3, 2011 |title= MLS Super Tuesday Raw: Sigi Pregame Presser|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SWDA-_QdBKU&feature=feedu |medium=YouTube|publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=October 3, 2011}}</ref> Grazzini began the game on the bench for Chicago.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>

=== First half ===
[[File:Fucito Johnson 2011 USOC Final.jpg|thumb|Fire goalkeeper Sean Johnson saves a scoring attempt by Seattle's Mike Fucito in the first half.|alt=A player in a blue goalkeeper uniform stands with his hands extended over a player in a yellow uniform sliding on the ground. A ball is bouncing away from the players.]]The match started with a frenetic pace as both teams earned free kick attempts within the opening two minutes.<ref name="Cup.us_report"/>  Seattle forward Mike Fucito had the first goal scoring opportunity of the match in the eighth minute as he broke free in the penalty area and took a shot on goal.  The shot was kicked away by Fire goalkeeper Sean Johnson.<ref name="MLS_report"/> Neither side appeared to gain control as the match progressed through the first 10 minutes.<ref name="Cup.us_report">{{cite web |url=http://thecup.us/2011-us-open-cup-final-seattle-sounders-smother-fire-earn-historic-three-peat-in-front-of-record-crowd/ |title=2011 US Open Cup Final: Seattle Sounders smother Fire, earn historic three-peat in front of record crowd |first=Gerald |last=Barnhart |date=October 5, 2011 |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref>  In the 11th minute, Chicago midfielder Marco Pappa slipped between two defenders in the middle of the field and had a long range shot go just wide of the net.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  Two minutes later Pappa again had a long shot which forced Seattle goalkeeper Kasey Keller to make a save.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/> Pappa was responsible for all five of his team's shots in the first half.<ref name="MLS_report"/>  In the 26th minute, Patrick Nyarko was shown a [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow card]] by referee Alex Prus for a hard tackle on Seattle's Osvaldo Alonso near the [[touch-line]].<ref name="Cup.us_report"/>

As the match passed the 30 minute mark, Seattle began to take control as they held possession and created more scoring opportunities.<ref name="Cup.us_report"/>  Five minutes before half time Marco Pappa again tested the Seattle goalkeeper as he cut inside a defender and took a shot from 30 yards.  The shot forced Kasey Keller to make a diving save.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  In the 44th minute Seattle striker Mike Fucito rushed onto a poor backpass by the Chicago defense and then backhealed a pass to Alvaro Fernandez who was streaking into the box.  His shot was stopped with a reaching save by Chicago goalkeeper Sean Johnson.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/><ref name="MLS_report"/> One minute later, in first half injury time, Seattle striker Fredy Montero nearly scored with a 20-yard shot that flew past the keeper and bounced off the left goal post.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/><ref name="MLS_report"/> The half ended with the score tied 0<U+2013>0.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>

=== Second half ===
[[File:Montero 2011 USOC Final.jpg|thumb|left|Sounders FC striker Fredy Montero celebrates after scoring his goal.|alt=Two players in yellow raise hands in celebration while several players in red stand behind them.]]At half time, Seattle midfielder Erik Frieberg was subbed on for Alvaro Fernandez, who had suffered a slight concussion during the first half.<ref name="MLS_report"/><ref name="SeattleTimes_quotes">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016406478_sounders_fc_2_chicago_fire_0_o.html |title=Sounders FC 2, Chicago Fire 0, Open Cup quotes and stats |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 4, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 28, 2012}}</ref>  Shortly after the second half began, Seattle nearly broke the stalemate.  In the 53rd minute, a Sounders FC [[throw-in]] was flicked on to Mike Fucito, who lifted a shot up and over the keeper.  His shot was chased by several Chicago defenders as it crossed the [[Association football pitch#Goals|goal mouth]] and bounced off the far [[goal post]] and back into play.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/><ref name="MLS_report"/>  In the 78th minute, Montero broke the deadlock on a [[corner kick]] taken by Erik Friberg.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/><ref name="Cup.us_report"/> Sounders FC defender Jeff Parke headed the corner kick on goal and Chicago goalkeeper Sean Johnson saved the shot.  The ball [[Rebound (sports)|rebounded]] to the feet of Fredy Montero, who tapped the ball into the net for in the first goal of the game.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/><ref name="SeattleTimes_report">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sounders/2016406004_sounders05.html |title=Sounders FC earns third straight Open Cup title |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 4, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=May 28, 2012}}</ref> Sounders FC now had a 1&ndash;0 lead.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>

For much of the first half and early second half, Sounders FC's defensive efforts had been focused on closely defending Chicago midfield P<U+00E1>vel Pardo.  With Pardo unable to distribute the ball to Chicago's speedy wingers, Patrick Nyarko and Domonic Oduro, Chicago's offense had been effectively neutralized for much of the match.<ref name="MLS_report2"/> Fire coach Frank Klopas made two substitutions late in the match, bringing on forward Diego Chaves in the 80th minute and midfielder Sebasti<U+00E1>n Grazzini in the 85th.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  Chicago's best chance of the half came in the 90th minute when Dominic Oduro headed a shot toward Kasey Keller, who made the save even though the attempt was ruled offside.<ref name="MLS_report">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/10/04/usoc-sounders-edge-fire-claim-3rd-straight-crown |title=USOC: Sounders edge Fire to claim 3rd straight crown |first=Andrew |last=Winner |date=October 4, 2011 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name="MLS_report2">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2011/10/05/usoc-sounders-douse-fires-attacking-threats-win |title=USOC: Sounders douse Fire's attacking threats in win |first=Andrew |last=Winner |date=October 5, 2011 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>
 
As the match neared its conclusion, Chicago shifted players forward as they searched for an equalizing goal.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/> However, in the sixth minute of [[stoppage time]], Osvaldo Alonso scored Seattle's second goal on a counterattack play as he dribbled around multiple defenders and the goalkeeper and finally tapped the ball into the net.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  The goal gave Sounders FC a 2<U+2013>0 lead and sealed the victory.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>

