== Post-match ==
[[File:2009, 2010, and 2011 U.S. Open Cups.JPG|thumb|The 2009, 2010 and 2011 U.S. Open Cups on display prior to a Sounders FC match in 2011.|alt=Three trophies placed in a line on a stage.]]
Most of the record crowd remained after the game as they watched Seattle players and coaches engaged in the post match trophy awarding ceremony and celebrated on the field.<ref name="TNT_post_match">{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/05/sounders-enjoy-spoils-of-us-cup-victory |title=Sounders enjoy spoils of Open Cup victory |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 5, 2011 |newspaper=Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>  In the post match press conference, Sigi Schmid praised his team's defensive efforts in the match, saying "We talked about making sure their defenders <U+2013> and primarily P<U+00E1>vel Pardo <U+2013> didn<U+2019>t have a chance to lift their heads and hit those long balls in behind." Schmid continued, "I thought Evans did a really good job. Sometimes we were stretched in the midfield, but I thought he did a very good job of stepping up to P<U+00E1>vel. When you look at the 90 minutes, it was a rare occasion that he was able to hit a ball behind our defense."<ref name="MLS_report2"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/04/sounders-coach-reacts-to-open-cup-win/ |title=Sounders coach reacts to Open Cup win |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 4, 2011 |newspaper=The Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>  Chicago midfielder Logan Pause commented on the game saying, "It<U+2019>s disappointing. We came here to win. We were under the gun all night. They<U+2019>re a great team, one of the best in the league. It was a great atmosphere and home field advantage. The better team won tonight unfortunately."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/04/fire-coach-its-not-an-easy-place/ |title=Fire coach: Clink 'not an easy place' |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 4, 2011 |newspaper=The Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>

The day after the match, Sounders FC flew a {{convert|3000|sqft|m2|lk=in|sigfig=2|adj=on}} scarf over Seattle and Bellevue in the afternoon and early evening respectively, in celebration of their victory.<ref name="USOC_notes">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/soundersfcblog/2016416313_video_of_the_impressive_ecs_ti.html |title=Video of the impressive ECS tifo and other Open Cup notes |first=Joshua |last=Mayers |date=October 5, 2011 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref> By winning the final, Sounders FC became the first MLS team to win the competition three times in a row, and the first club to do so in the competition since [[Greek American AA|Greek American Atlas]] did so in [[1968 U.S. Open Cup|1968]], 42 years earlier. Seattle also became the fourth team in the 98-year history of the tournament to win three in a row.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  As U.S. Open Cup champions, Seattle received the $100,000 cash prize while Chicago was given $50,000 as the runner up.<ref name="USSoccer_report"/>  Seattle also earned a berth in the [[2012<U+2013>13 CONCACAF Champions League]] with the victory.<ref name="TNT_post_match"/> In the Champions League, Seattle won their group and were eventually knocked out of the tournament in the semifinals by Mexican club [[Santos Laguna]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2013-04-02-SEA-v-CSL/recap |title=CCL Match Recap: Seattle Sounders 0, Santos Laguna 1 |first=Andrew |last=Wiebe |date=April 2, 2013 |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref>

Sounders FC midfielder Osvaldo Alonso was voted the "player of the round" for the final.<ref name="MVP1"/><ref name="MVP2"/>  Alonso was recognized for his goal scoring effort as well as his record-setting fourth consecutive appearance as a player in the U.S. Open Cup final match.  He had appeared first with the [[Charleston Battery]] in the 2008 final and then 3 times with Seattle from 2009 to 2011.<ref name="MVP2"/> Seattle forward Fredy Montero was recognized as the "player of the tournament" as he scored the game winning goals for Sounders FC in their quarterfinal, semifinal, and final matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecup.us/seattle-sounders-fredy-montero-named-2011-thecup-us-player-of-the-tournament/ |title=Seattle Sounders<U+2019> Fredy Montero named 2011 TheCup.us Player of the Tournament |first=Gerald |last=Barnhart |date=October 13, 2011 |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref> Osvaldo Alonso was one of the four finalists for "player of the tournament" along with Montero and two players from the semifinalist Richmond Kickers&ndash;[[Ronnie Pascale]] and [[David Bulow]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecup.us/2011-us-open-cup-finalists-for-thecup-us-player-of-the-tournament-unveiled/ |title=2011 US Open Cup: Finalists for TheCup.us Player of the Tournament unveiled |first=Gerald |last=Barnhart |date=October 11, 2011 |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>

=== Host selection process changes ===
U.S. Soccer was criticized after the match for the secretive bid process that allows teams to outspend their opponents for hosting rights.  Both the blind bidding process for hosting tournament matches and the manner in which MLS teams qualified for the tournament were widely criticized.<ref name="AOL_rule_changes">{{cite news |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/soccer/story/2011-10-05/us-open-cup-should-be-revamped-for-12 |title=U.S. Open Cup Could be Revamped for '12 |work=The Sporting News |date=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=October 6, 2011 |author=Straus, Brian}}</ref>  An example of the concerns raised around hosting came from FC Dallas midfielder [[Daniel Hernandez (soccer)|Daniel Hernandez]] on [[Twitter]], where he complained about Seattle's [[home-field advantage]] throughout the 2011 tournament.<ref name="USOC_notes"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/05/hoops-hernandez-is-a-troll-with-a-point/ |title=FC Dallas' Hernandez is a Troll&nbsp;... With a Point |work=The News Tribune |date=October 5, 2011 |accessdate=October 6, 2011 |author=Ruiz, Don |location=Tacoma}}</ref>  Following the final, MLS and U.S. Soccer officials met to discuss rule changes to the tournament's host bidding system and team qualification processes.<ref name="AOL_rule_changes"/>  Sounders FC owner Adrian Hanauer commented on the changes and the possibility of raising the profile of the tournament, "I don<U+2019>t think the bidding process is going to change the profile of the tournament, necessarily. It might make a few people happy, it might make a few people unhappy. But ultimately, I<U+2019>m not convinced that<U+2019>s what is going to raise the profile."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/soccer/2011/10/06/hanauer-wants-voice-in-cup-changes/ |title=Hanauer wants voice in Open Cup changes |first=Don |last=Ruiz |date=October 6, 2011 |newspaper=The Tacoma News Tribune |accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>

In January 2012, in preparation for the [[2012 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|2012 edition]] of the U.S. Open Cup, U.S. Soccer announced several changes to the tournament format.  Included in these changes was the introduction of a new host selection process.  Beginning in 2012, for all rounds of the tournament through the quarterfinals, a random host selection process would be used.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2012/01/2012-Open-Cup.aspx |title=Format, Composition and Schedule Finalized for 99th Edition of Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup |date=January 11, 2012 |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Lamar-Hunt-U-S-Open-Cup/2012/01/Open-Cup-Sidebar.aspx |title=Lower-Division Teams Relish Chance to Host Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Matches |date=January 11, 2012 |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> While in previous years a blind bidding system was used to determine the host of a match, the new process has the host determined by blind draw if both teams' venues meet minimum standards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecup.us/more-details-revealed-on-new-us-open-cup-hosting-process/ |title=More details revealed on new US Open Cup hosting process |first=Josh |last=Hakala |date=May 29, 2012 |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> The blind bidding system for hosting rights remained in effect for the semifinals and final of the 2012 tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecup.us/ussf-announces-monumental-format-changes-to-2012-us-open-cup/ |title=USSF announces monumental format changes to 2012 US Open Cup |first=Josh |last=Hakala |date=January 11, 2012 |publisher=TheCup.us |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref>  However, U.S. Soccer announced in 2013 that hosting for all rounds of the tournament would be determined randomly as long as both venues met minimum standards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/news/lamar-hunt-u-s-open-cup/2013/03/2013-us-lamar-hunt-us-open-cup-release.aspx |title=100th Edition of Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Includes Increased Number of Teams and Prize Money |date=March 5, 2013 |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref>

